WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Thanks, Hari. Yeah, good morning, folks. Happy to be here.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I find a good bit of AI discourse pretty annoying.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:20.000
If you're a LinkedIn user, you've probably seen a post that looks something like this before,

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
where it starts out with some, like, vague, bold assertion, like,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
AI will change everything about data science.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And then, like, in order to read anything about the actual content of the post,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
you have to, like, click in and actually engage, so it gets a boost in the algorithm.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
And then there's some sort of picture, usually the imagery we've converged on is a humanoid robot

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:54.000
typing on something between a laptop and a desktop, and it has, like, 200 keys on the keyboard.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:04.000
There's a lot of what data science looks like in the real world that doesn't get represented in this sort of post.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:16.000
So in these posts, for one, robots, or in reality, API keys to LLMs, are free or happily paid for by someone else.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
So when these new big feature drops happen from the major labs,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
they're often quite expensive.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And even the ones that have been around for almost a year now, like Cloud Code,

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
a day of development where you're really just using the tool for eight hours,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
you can rack up 50 or 100 bucks in billing easily.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Another sort of assumption that underlies a lot of these posts is that the data being scienced

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
can just be sent straight to OpenAI servers or Anthropic servers or Googles,

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:59.000
when in reality, the data that many of us work on day to day is confidential,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
and we can't just send it over to any company that tells us they can do interesting things with it.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And finally, there's often this assumption that data science can be one-shotted,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:19.000
which is this term in the AI space, meaning you just like pass along your data,

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.000
and then you like go make a coffee or have lunch or something,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
and you come back to a complete analysis.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
There's a lot about real world data science that doesn't get represented when we make these assumptions.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
So in reality, for one, Frontier LLMs cost money, right?

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Even like technologies like Cloud Code, again, if you're using it all day,

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
you can easily rack up a bill that you probably don't want to foot yourself.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Data science happens on mostly sensitive and confidential data.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
So whether that results from clinical trials or you're pulling something from an EMR,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
this data is subject to privacy constraints that we have to be conscious of.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And so you can't just make use of the latest and greatest from any lab if you need those privacy guarantees.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And finally, in the real world, data science is messy and it's subtle and it's context-rich.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:28.000
The problems that data scientists solve day-to-day aren't just like data set in, insight out.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
There's all sorts of context and understanding that we bring to data science.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Integration with data sources and tools that are outside of maybe the most obvious choices.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:52.000
And so data science really needs that like real human cognition that LLMs can be proxies for, but don't truly have.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So I'm not just going to be ragging on folks on LinkedIn throughout the rest of this talk.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
I want to focus on two big ideas.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
The first one is that I'd like to show what's currently possible in R with Elmer.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:11.000
Elmer is a package that lets you talk to LLMs in R.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
It's made leaps and bounds over the last year.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
And I think it's like the best interface to program against LLMs that there is.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And then I also want to speak to specifically the constraints that people doing data science in organizations,

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:32.000
and specifically in organizations like those in pharma, what that data science actually looks like,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
what using LLMs in those circumstances actually looks like.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And so I want to help you imagine making it work in practice.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
But we'll start first with a glimpse of what's possible in R.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Again, the Elmer package is a package that allows you to talk to LLMs in R.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:00.000
And it enables three sort of boosts for data science that I think are underappreciated.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And it enables three sort of boosts for data science that I think are underappreciated.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I want to go through those three in order.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
The first is about extracting structured data from unstructured data.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So that could be free text fields that live in an EMR or result from some clinical trial.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Those could be images.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:35.000
LLMs are incredible when situated in the right way to extract structured data from these unstructured sources.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The next thing is tool calling.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Tool calling is a way to give LLMs the ability to run deterministic, quote, normal software.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And equipping LLMs with tool calling fills in a lot of the gaps in these LLMs in terms of the things that they're not good at that we would think they'd be good at and otherwise.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Or vice versa.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And then finally, coding and specifically coding agents.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:14.000
LLMs are quite strong in terms of generating code to carry out a given task.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And so if you provide them with the right scaffold, you provide them with true human cognition, they can be really helpful in writing data science code.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:32.000
So we'll start out with just a quick intro into what it looks like to talk to an LLM via Elmer in the first place.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And there's sort of three high level steps here.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.000
The first one is loading the package.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:43.000
The second is creating this chat object.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:53.000
There are something like 20 different functions inside of Elmer that start with this chat underscore, and then they have the name of some sort of provider.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:00.000
So that could be like one of the three major labs, Anthropic, OpenAI, or Google Gemini.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
That could also be like a local model on your own machine, like chat-olama.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:15.000
And that could also be a private or secure deployment of an LLM that your organization might have deployed.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So if your organization uses Bedrock or Databricks or Snowflake or some other private vendor, you can probably connect to that vendor via Elmer.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
But regardless, whichever provider that you choose, you end up with this chat object.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And the chat object has a bunch of methods attached to it.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So you can put a dollar sign after, and there's all sorts of functions that can act on the chat object.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And so we'll use this dollar sign chat object or chat function, which is the easiest entry point to start talking to these LLMs.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So I could say something like, who are you?

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And because I have made a connection to this Anthropic API, I'm talking to CloudSonic, and the model will tell me that it's Cloud.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Through this interface, we can take advantage of those three different capabilities to do data science.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So first, we'll talk about turning unstructured data into structured data.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
How are our regex chops in the crowd?

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:45.000
If I saw a set of sentences like this, and I needed to extract name and age from this data, I don't even know that I could write a regex that makes this happen.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
I don't even know if that's possible.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:58.000
These are sort of contrived examples, but we can imagine in recordings of patient conversations or interviews through a clinical trial or something,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:06.000
we have all sorts of these unstructured free text fields, and we need to extract information from them.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So we have these six different sentences where at some point somebody says their name and their age.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And using traditional software, using something like regex, this would be a really difficult problem to solve.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
This is something that LLMs are actually quite good at.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So using that chat function, we could say something like, extract the name and age from each sentence I give you, and then just pass through each of those sentences one by one.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:44.000
As you can see in these results, the LLM is quite good at pulling out both of those pieces of information.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:55.000
This does kind of put us in a situation where we still need to use regex, where the LLM has outputted more free text,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:03.000
and it just says star star name colon star star, and then the name, and it does a similar thing for the age.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
So we would still have to process that a little bit.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
It turns out that we can do that explicitly.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:19.000
We can get an output that looks a little bit more like this, a normal R list where there's a name field and an age field.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:31.000
The way that we do that is via a different method on this same object, and that method, instead of being called chat, is called chat structured.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:40.000
So we pass in the prompt just as before, but we also pass in this type object.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.000
Type objects are just specifications of the format of the response that you would like to get back.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So in our example, we can say we want the name, and that's going to be a string.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And then we want the age, and that's going to be a number.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And if we pass that along, we can get an R list back with the name and age.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:11.000
This sort of thing is super useful from going to free text, unstructured data, to tables.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:15.000
Gets you to happy data frame land as quickly as possible.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And you don't just have to do this one by one.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
You can do this in parallel with Elmer.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
It has a function called parallel chat structured.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:33.000
This is parallel in the sense of a ton of HTTP requests being sent off at once and then collected as they come back,

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
not in the sense of spinning a bunch of R processes up on your machine.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And so this means that you can pass along all six of those prompts at once,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:47.000
and using a model like Cloud Sonic, you get a response back in a second or something like that.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And so this enables you to process that data at the scale that you actually need to.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:01.000
It's not just text that you can use this structured data extraction with.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
You can also do so with images.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So if we imagine that I have this directory called animals,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
and there's a bunch of paths to images inside of that directory,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:19.000
I can use a function content image file on each of those paths in the directory,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.000
load in the image, and then pass them along in the same way using parallel chat structured.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:31.000
So if I have these images of animals and I want to know which animal it is and what the background color of the picture is,

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
I can also specify that in a type object and send it along.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So you can imagine inside of a clinical trial, if there's like imagery or some other image information that is collected as part of the trial,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:52.000
you can process it with these models.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:58.000
So at a high level, this is what's possible with structured data extraction with LLMs.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:06.000
And this is like such a useful tool in getting yourself into a data frame that you know how to work with,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:13.000
with your usual dplyr and tidyr and ggplot and things like that.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:19.000
The next capability that I want to talk about is something called tool calling.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And practically, this is a super helpful capability when you're trying to get LLMs to help you with certain tasks.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:35.000
So one thing that LLMs can't do is access real time information.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
This just isn't how they work.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
They have a knowledge cut off.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
They're trained on a bunch of information.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:47.000
Natively, they have no way to learn what the current date is.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:52.000
So if I initialize this chat object and I say, what day is it today?

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Cloud will respond to me and say, I don't know.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
If you're using a model like chat2pt.com or cloud.ai or whatever,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
they'll often inject that information into the prompt so that it appears that they do know what the date is.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:11.000
But that's like scaffolding on top of the model rather than the raw model itself.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:19.000
So what we can do is provide a tool to the model.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.000
A tool is just a function and then some documentation on how to use the function.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So, for example, I could make this tool called today, which gets today's date.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And all it does when it's called is just calls the sys.date function.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And so we describe this function as get today's date to the model.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
The function has no arguments.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
So we just provide an empty list.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And then we use yet another method on this chat object, which is the register tool method.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
This tool function here is exported from the Elmer package,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.000
and it just allows you to attach some metadata to a given function.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:06.000
And once you've done that, you can register it with the chat.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:13.000
So then if I go back to that chat object and I ask the same question, I say, what day is it today?

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:20.000
The model can choose to return a message back to me in this structured way,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.000
which Elmer will see and say, oh, this isn't a message that's intended for the user.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:31.000
This is a message that I can process myself and immediately return a response back.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:38.000
So the LLM decides to send me this special formatted message that says call this function today.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And the function returns the date at the moment at which it was called.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
So this is August 8th, 2025.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
So then it's again the model's turn to do whatever it wants to do.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:59.000
And in this case, it's just going to situate this response from the tool inside of its message back to you.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So it can say today is August 8th, 2025.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
And it happens to know that it's Friday because LLMs are weird.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
This is a strange concept to wrap your head around at first.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:19.000
So I just want to like actually diagram this out and make sure this is clear what's actually happening here.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
So this is me last week.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:29.000
And last week, I was having a conversation with this humanoid robot typing on a laptop slash desktop.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
So last week, I send this message over to the humanoid robot.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And I say, what day is it today?

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So the only thing that the model can do is respond back with another HTTP request.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:52.000
Except that it can format that request in such a way that Elmer will see the response.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.000
And it will realize that the response shouldn't be shown to me.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:00.000
So I never see this message, please call today.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Elmer sees it and it processes it automatically and returns the result back to the model.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:13.000
So again, the humanoid robot sends this specially formatted message that says, please call today.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
The response is returned to the robot.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And then the humanoid robot can situate that response in a response back to me.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So this is what we call a complete tool calling loop, where a model chooses to call a tool.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.000
It gets a response back, and then it chooses what to do next.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So often, a model can call a tool.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
It can observe the result.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And then once it observes the result, it can either respond back to me, as it did.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:57.000
Or it can just continue to call tools until it's accomplished the task that it would like to do.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:05.000
So this is like sort of a preview into tool calling.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:15.000
And now we'll situate tool calling inside of a scaffold where we're using tool calls to write and evaluate code.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:25.000
So LLMs, through their hazy recollection of the entire Internet, are pretty good at generating code.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:37.000
And if we give LLMs the ability to run code in a thoughtful way, we provide them with a scaffold that helps them assist us as best as they can.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:41.000
Then these models can be pretty helpful at generating data science code.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:47.000
So again, this is a callback to the tool calling loop.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:19:02.000
When people say coding agent, which is a pretty popular term now, this can refer to agents like Cloud Code or Codex, and also agents built by Posit, like Positron Assistant or Databot.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.000
This is LLMs calling tools in a loop.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:17.000
And usually, when we say something is an agent, we mean that those tools give the model the ability to read and write state.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.000
So what do I mean?

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:28.000
If I make a fresh chat object, and in that chat I say, delete the CSV files in my working directory.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:36.000
If the model were given the ability to run code, it could probably figure out how to do that pretty easily.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:49.000
So, for example, this model has chosen to show me how to do this in Bash if it were to be given the ability to run code, or it can just tell me this is the code that you would use to make that happen.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:20:01.000
What this model is not actually doing is going and deleting the CSV files, because it doesn't have tools that give it the ability to read and write state.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:15.000
And so in order to carry this out, the model needs to be able to actually find the files that it wants to delete in the first place, and then go and delete those files, which is writing state.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:20.000
We can do this with two Elmer tools.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:29.000
The first one we will call ls, and that just calls the dir function in R, which will list the files inside of the current directory.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:34.000
So this tool will give the model the ability to read state.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:54.000
Then we can provide a second tool called rm, and given a path, that path is just provided to the unlink function in R, and this tool will give the LM the ability to delete one or more files.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:02.000
As you can see, this list of arguments, I think this is the first time we've seen this in this talk.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:12.000
This looks very similar to the specification of the type of thing that we want to receive back when we're doing structured data extraction.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:24.000
So we provide this one argument to the LM, which is the path, and the model is given the ability to delete the files at that path.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:40.000
So using these two tools, first the model can read state to find the CSV files that it wants to delete, and then given this rm tool, it can actually go and delete those files.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:51.000
So if we return to that fresh chat again and ask the same question, delete all the CSV files in the current directory,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:22:03.000
the model can choose to call the ls tool, which will return a bunch of information about the objects that are inside of that directory.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:10.000
The model can identify which of those are CSVs and call another tool.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:30.000
So this is an example of that full tool calling loop, where the model calls a tool, it gets a response back, and before it says something and yields control back to the user, it decides to call another tool before it does so.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:41.000
So it will call this remove tool, and it will provide these two paths to the CSV files that it found, and then the tool will return.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:55.000
So in this case, because all the rm tool is doing is writing state, it just says, okay, I did that, done, which is what this true represents.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:04.000
And only at this point will the model complete the tool calling loop and yield back to the user saying, done, I deleted those files.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:22.000
So deleting CSV files in one's current directory is a nice example, but it's not necessarily something that we would make use of often in our data science work day to day.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:30.000
So I want to call out a couple of coding agents that we've been spending our time on at Posit, and hopefully you could find pretty compelling.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:41.000
The first of these is DataBot, which is an assistant for exploratory data analysis inside of Positron.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:49.000
When you install DataBot, it looks like a typical chat window, except that it has access to your active R environment.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:24:01.000
So imagine I've loaded this data already into my R session, it's called forested, I can tell the coding agent DataBot to go ahead and check that data out and make some ggplots.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:12.000
So first thing, the model will take a look at the data and make sure that it knows the column names to use and what those column types are.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:20.000
And then once it's done so, it'll glimpse that out through running R code and then start making ggplots.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:28.000
After a couple plots, the model will then yield control back to the user.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:41.000
And this is like one of the really nice, powerful parts about DataBot, which is that it's sort of tuned to just call a couple tools, push the analysis forward a little bit,

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:46.000
and then yield control back to the user, maybe provide some suggestions on where to go from there.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:50.000
But this really keeps the user in the loop through that process.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.000
So how is this agent reading and writing state?

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:09.000
Often in these applied contexts, the distinction between reading tools for reading state and writing state is a little bit blurred.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Because if you give a model the ability to run R code, generally, then it can do anything that it can do via bash even.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:31.000
So the run R code tool, which allows the model to write R code, and then see its results, as well as show the user the results, can both read and write state.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And then there's also this createCordoReport tool.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:47.000
So once you're finished with some EDA, you can take that initial analysis and situate it inside a persistent reproducible report.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:59.000
For more general coding assistance tasks, Positron comes with one more coding agent, which is called Positron Assistant.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And again, Assistant is focused a little bit more on coding than EDA specifically, but it can help along with some EDA as well.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:19.000
To demonstrate this, we can take that same forest data and imagine we have situated it inside of this readme file.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:27.000
I can ask the coding agent, could you add some ggplots to the end of this file?

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:40.000
And in this case, the model will read the readme.rmd file, it will take a look at the forested dataset, and then it will add some code to the end of the file.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:49.000
Positron Assistant is especially nice because it's really tightly integrated with many different elements of the IDE.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:56.000
So it can see your active R session, it can see the files you have open, and it's really easy to give it the right context.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:13.000
Positron Assistant's tools for reading and writing state are pretty similar to generic coding agents like Cloud Code or Codex that you might have heard of before.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:20.000
But there's also these special tools that allow it to access different parts of the IDE.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:29.000
And its implementations of tools display tool requests really nicely inside of the interface.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:42.000
So, for example, if the Positron Assistant wants to edit a file, like adding those lines to the readme, that's displayed nicely in that diff format inside of the editor.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
So it's really easy to see the changes that it wants to make.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:51.000
So up to this point, I've just talked about coding agents for Positron.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:28:05.000
I know that many of the folks here are probably still RStudio users, and I want to call out a quick coding agent that I've been spending some time on in recent weeks, and I hope you might be able to get some use from it.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:09.000
That coding agent is called Sidekick.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:15.000
Sidekick is built entirely in R, and it runs inside of a Shiny app.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:28.000
So if you run this function side colon colon kick, the first thing that it will do is spin up a Shiny app that runs in a background job inside of RStudio.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:42.000
And it's a little hard to see because the viewer here has a little background, but there's a Shiny app pulled up on the left here that allows you to converse with the LLM via Elmer.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:50.000
So Sidekick can do normal Cloud Code codex coding agent sort of tasks.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:58.000
So for one, we could ask this agent to refactor some code into a helper.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:08.000
So these six lines, seven lines are pretty constrained in what they do, and we could probably make use of it in a few different places inside this package.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:18.000
So the model will first choose to run this code search tool that will help it find the code that I just passed along to it.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:27.000
And then it will read the whole file once it finds the function or the lines of code that I mentioned.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:45.000
Once it's found those lines of code, it can then propose edits to the files using an edit files tool, and that tool will display the changes that the model wants to make inside of a nice diff format.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:54.000
You can choose to reject or approve the edits, but once you've approved them, those changes will show up inside of the real files.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:00.000
You can also start new chats and chats are persistent inside of Sidekick.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:07.000
So the Sidekick agent is also able to run our code inside of the active session.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:16.000
It can see your active session and you'll be able to see the results of the code that it runs nicely formatted inside of this UI.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:24.000
So if you've had an eye out for a coding agent for RStudio, I would encourage you to give Sidekick a try.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:33.000
This is freely available on my GitHub in the link shown at the bottom, and this will also be in the notes for the talk that I'll share at the end.

